The opposition says the announcement of a preliminary investigation to determine the merits of the allegations doesn&#8217;t extend far enough. CAPE TOWN The Democratic Alliance (DA) is calling on the Public Protector to widen her probe into the Gupta emails matter that points to state capture at Eskom, Prasa and Transnet.The opposition says the announcement of a preliminary investigation to determine the merits of the allegations doesn t extend far enough.DA leader Mmusi Maimane says Busisiwe Mkhwebane is cherry-picking which institutions and people to investigate while ignoring the alleged role of President Jacob Zuma, Cabinet ministers and the Gupta family through their companies.Maimane s spokesperson Graham Charters says: The Gupta-controlled families and ministers that are linked to the Gupta family are the real power brokers in state capture, it s not paid officials within Eskom and Transnet and Prasa. MKHWEBANE ANNOUNCES PROBEThe Public Protector's office says it will be looking into a number of allegations made by the media, including the reappointment of Brian Molefe as Eskom CEO and allegations that acting chief executive Matshela Koko leaked a legal opinion to the Guptas.Mkhwebane has announced that she will investigate improper or unlawful enrichment and improper advantage by public officials at Eskom, the Passenger Rail Agency of South Africa and Transnet.She is also investigating allegations around Duduzane Zuma and the Gupta s and how the controversial family received classified information from former Communication Minister Faith Muthambi.Spokesperson Cleopatra Mosana says the legality of the Gupta s business operations in the country will also be looked into. It s the allegations of the Guptas who have received high-level confidential information from the then Communication Minister Faith Muthambi and allegations that at least two immigration officials were positioned in Indian by the then Minister of Home Affairs to assist the Guptas in benefiting in businesses. (Edited by Leeto M Khoza)